\layout Section

Introduction 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Introduction}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars (TTS) are young (
\begin_inset Formula $<\sim3\times10^{6}\,\mathrm{yrs}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{appenzeller:1989}
\end_inset 

) low-mass stars, and known as progenitors of solar-type stars.
 Classical T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars (CTTS) exhibit strong H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission, and typically have spectral types of F--K.
 Some of the most active CTTS show emission in higher Balmer lines and metal
 lines (e.g., Ca\SpecialChar ~
II H and K).
 They also exhibit an excess amount of continuum flux in the ultraviolet
 (UV) and infrared (IR).
 
\layout Standard

Line profile studies of CTTS show that the evidence for both outward wind
 flows and inward accretion flows, as seen in the blueshifted absorption
 features in H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{herbig:1962}
\end_inset 

) and the inverse P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni (IPC) profiles (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kenyon:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{edwards:1994}
\end_inset 

) respectively.
 Typical mass-loss rates of CTTS are about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-9}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kuhi:1964}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{edwards:1987}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartigan:1995}
\end_inset 

), and the mass-accretion rates are also about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-9}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kenyon:1987}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{bertout:1988}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{gullbring:1998}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

In a currently favoured model of accretion flows around CTTS, the accretion
 discs are disrupted by the magnetosphere of stars which channels the gas
 from the disc onto the surface of the stars (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{uchida:1985}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:1991}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{cameron:1993}
\end_inset 


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{shu:1994}
\end_inset 

).
 This picture of the accretion flows is supported by the evidences that
 CTTS have relatively strong (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{3}\mathrm{G}$
\end_inset 

) magnetic field (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{jonhs-krull:1999}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{guenther:1996}
\end_inset 

) and by the radiative transfer models which reproduce the observed profiles
 for some TTS (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

).
